  │ The least-upper-bound property is a characteristic of an ordered set \(S\) stating that for any non-empty subset \(E\) of \(S\) that is bounded above, the supremum (least upper bound) of \(E\) exists within \(S\) [Source: data/local/rudin_ch15.pdf]. This means the set \(S\) contains an element that is the smallest among all upper bounds of any such subset. For example, the ordered set of rational numbers \( \mathbf{Q} \) does **not** possess this property, as shown by a set like \( \{x \in \mathbf{Q} : x^2 < 2\} \) which is bounded above but has no least upper bound in \( \mathbf{Q} \) [Source: data/local/rudin_ch15.pdf.ocr.md].
